Wow! Cool concept! It was very fun to solve, but unfortunately, it took more than 15 minutes for me to code my solution (in Python3). I'm not even a noob either, so if it took that long for me, then imagine all the beginners who would struggle so badly when they play this. Maybe I just suck, but this might be too hard for most. Nonetheless, the concept is really nice!

Below was the solution that I coded that took >15 minutes. You can see that your puzzle really shook me up, and I dunno if a beginner stands any chance.
import sys
import math

# Auto-generated code below aims at helping you parse
# the standard input according to the problem statement.
s=""
w, h = [int(i) for i in input().split()]
b=[]
for i in range(h):
    line = input()
    s+=line
    k=[]
    for j in line:
        k.append(j)
    b.append(k)
x=y=m=n=0
for ie,i in enumerate(b):
    for je,j in enumerate(i):
        if s.count(j)==1:
            x=je
            y=ie
            m=j
        else:
            n=j


# Write an answer using print
print([x,y,m,n], file=sys.stderr, flush=True)
for ie,i in enumerate(b):
    for je,j in enumerate(i):
        if ie==y and je==x:print(end=str(m))
        else:
            if je==x:
                if (ie+2==y or ie-2==y):
                    print(end="|")
                elif ie+1==y:
                    print(end="v")
                elif ie-1==y:
                    print(end="^")
                else:print(end=str(n))
            elif ie==y:
                if (je-2==x or je+2==x):
                    print(end="-")
                elif je+1==x:
                    print(end=">")
                elif je-1==x:
                    print(end="<")
                else:print(end=str(n))
            else:print(end=str(n))
    print()
